&gt; my main question is what problems can be when constructor throw an exception

just as with throwing in general, there&#39;s nothing specific about a constructor. 

C++ is designed to have throws in constructors.

Your example:

    m = new int(y);
    throw std::exception();

is bad anywhere.

Use:

    auto m = std::make_unique&lt;int&gt;(y);
    throw std::exception();

instead.

